    scripture: "And he said, Come. And when Peter was come down out of the ship, he walked on the water, to go to Jesus.",
    walk: `It was the middle of the night, friend, and the storm was raging. The disciples were straining at the oars when they saw Jesus walking toward them on the water. Peter, impulsive as ever, called out, "Lord, if it be thou, bid me come unto thee on the water." And Jesus said one word: Come. And Peter did the impossible — he walked on the water, to go to Jesus.

We often remember this story for the part where Peter sinks. But don't rush past what he did first: he walked on water. He got out of the boat in a storm and did something no natural law allows, because Jesus said come and he believed enough to step out. However the story ends, Peter is the only person besides Jesus who ever walked on the sea — and he did it because he was willing to leave the boat.

Here's the truth, friend: faith requires getting out of the boat. The boat is safety. The boat is the familiar, the controllable, the place where you can explain everything. And Jesus often calls us to step out of it — onto water, into the impossible, toward Him. You cannot walk on water while you're still holding onto the boat. At some point, faith means letting go of what feels secure and stepping out onto nothing but the word of Jesus.

Yes, Peter sank when he took his eyes off Christ and looked at the wind. But even then, the story is full of grace: he cried "Lord, save me," and immediately Jesus caught him. Peter got to feel the grip of Jesus' hand precisely because he'd been bold enough to get out of the boat. The eleven who stayed dry never felt that hand.

So when Jesus says come today, friend, don't stay in the boat. Step out toward Him. Keep your eyes on His face, not the waves. And if you start to sink, He's near enough to catch you in an instant.`,
    prayer: `Jesus, when You say "come," give me the courage to get out of the boat. I want to step toward You even onto the impossible, keeping my eyes on Your face instead of the storm. And when I start to sink, thank You that You catch me immediately. Help me trust You enough to let go of safety. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Name your "boat" — the safe, familiar thing you're gripping. Today, take one step out of it toward what Jesus is calling you to, keeping your eyes fixed on Him.`,
