    ref: "Joshua 1:9",
    scripture: "Have not I commanded thee? Be strong and of a good courage; be not afraid, neither be thou dismayed: for the LORD thy God is with thee whithersoever thou goest.",
    walk: `Joshua was about to lead an entire nation into a land full of enemies, friend, stepping into shoes left by Moses, facing a task far bigger than himself. He had every reason to be afraid. And so God speaks these words to him — words for everyone who has to do something hard and frightening: Be strong and of a good courage; be not afraid.

Notice that God commands courage. Have not I commanded thee? Be strong. That's striking, because we usually think of courage as a feeling — either you have it or you don't. But God treats courage as a choice, something you can decide to do even when you don't feel it. Courage isn't the absence of fear; it's moving forward in obedience while you're afraid. God wouldn't command Joshua not to fear if fear weren't real and present. He's saying: feel the fear, and step forward anyway.

But God doesn't just demand courage and leave Joshua to find it on his own. He gives the reason for the courage, and it's the only reason that ever really holds: for the LORD thy God is with thee whithersoever thou goest. The command to be brave rests entirely on the promise of His presence. You can be strong, not because you're strong enough, but because the One going with you is.

This is faith that moves forward, friend. It does the frightening thing — the hard conversation, the new beginning, the obedient step — not because the fear has disappeared, but because God is with you in it. Wherever you go, He goes. Whatever you face, you don't face it alone.

So if God is calling you to something that scares you today, friend, don't wait for the fear to lift. Be strong and of good courage — do it afraid — because the Lord your God is with you wherever you go. His presence is the courage you've been waiting to feel.`,
    prayer: `Father, You command me to be strong and courageous, and to not be afraid. I confess the fear is real — but I will move forward anyway, because You promise to be with me wherever I go. Be my courage today. Help me do the hard thing, knowing I never do it alone. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
