    walk: `You've reached the final day, friend, and the destination of the whole journey: the day faith becomes sight. For twenty-one days we've learned to walk by faith and not by sight — to trust God in the gap between the promise and the seeing. But this verse promises that the gap will not last forever. One day, the seeing comes.

For now we see through a glass, darkly. The mirrors of Paul's day were polished metal, giving only a dim, blurry reflection. That's how we see now — in part, through a clouded glass. We don't get the full picture. We don't understand why the answer was delayed, why the road went through the dark, why God did it this way and not that. We see enough to trust, but not enough to fully understand. And that's the nature of this life: we walk by faith, seeing dimly.

But then face to face. There's coming a day, friend, when the glass is gone — when we'll see God not dimly but face to face, clearly, fully, with nothing in between. Now I know in part; but then shall I know even as also I am known. Every question will be answered. Every delay will make sense. Every dark stretch we walked by faith will be flooded with light, and we'll see the whole beautiful purpose of it all.

That's the hope that makes walking by faith worth it. We're not trusting in the dark forever. We're walking toward a morning when faith turns to sight, when we finally see the face of the One we've been trusting all along. Every prayer prayed into apparent silence, every promise believed before it came to pass — all of it will be vindicated in that face-to-face day.

So keep walking by faith, friend. The dim glass is temporary. The face-to-face is forever. The God you've trusted without seeing, you will one day see — and you will know, even as you are known. Faith will become sight.`,
    prayer: `Father, thank You that walking by faith won't last forever — that one day faith becomes sight, and I'll see You face to face. When I see dimly now and don't understand, help me keep trusting You. I'm walking toward the day when every question is answered in Your presence. Hold me till then. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Look back over these twenty-one days. Thank God for one way He's grown your faith — and choose one promise to keep "walking by faith" on, trusting that one day it will become sight.`,
